                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d573">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">550.S1 Monetary Commission/58</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chief of the Treaty Division</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Barnes</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-01-17">January 17,
                            1934</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Barnes</hi>: I took this matter up with the President
                    yesterday and asked him to initial his O. K., if he approved, opposite the
                    second paragraph of Senator Pittman’s letter. Inadvertently he initialed at the
                    top of the letter,<note n="16" xml:id="d573fn16">The notation was as follows:
                        “This is O. K. FDR Jan 16” (550. S1 Monetary Commission/57).</note> but you
                    may take his O. K. as indicating that the proclamation constitutes
                    ratification.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
